\begin_layout Section
HO-Model Intro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

{
\backslash
LARGE 
\backslash
textbf{Heckscher-Ohlin Model}}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
HO Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the Ricardian model, we assumed that technological differences in production
 is what gives rise to specialization and trade
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We also assumed that only one factor is used in production
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Although the Ricardian model was able to make predictions about welfare,
 the worst that could happen to a country is that welfare does not change
 following trade
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
No welfare loss when moving from autarky to trade
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
HO Model
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To introduce the possibility of welfare losses, we introduce another factor
 in production
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This will allow us to make a prediction on how the income of one factor
 is affected relative to the income of the other factor following trade
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Another key difference between the Ricardian model and the HO model is the
 source of trade
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Ricardian: technological differences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
HO: factor abundance
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Model Environment / Assumptions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Model Environment and Assumptions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Two countries: North and South
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two goods: Computers and Textiles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Two factors: Capital (K) and Labour (L)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
K: buildings, machinery
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The supply of K and L in each country is fixed, but it varies across the
 two countries
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Constant returns to scale in production
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
scale inputs by a factor of 2, output increases by a factor of 2
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Perfect competition
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
firms take prices as given, marginal revenue = marginal cost
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Both factors are mobile across sectors but not across countries
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
this will equalize their returns (wage and rental rate) across sectors within
 a country
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Model Environment and Assumptions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume that North's stock of factors is such that they have a 
\series bold
relative abundance
\series default
 of capital
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{K^{N}}{L^{N}}>\frac{K^{S}}{L^{S}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We will focus on relative factor abundance (not absolute)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Similar to the distinction made between comparative and absolute advantage
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Model Environment and Assumptions
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The production functions for the two goods are
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{C}(K_{C},L_{C})\ \text{and}\ F_{T}(K_{T},L_{T})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the Ricardian model, we just had 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}(L)=\frac{1}{a_{C}}L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These production functions will be increasing in each input, but at diminishing
 rates
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial F(K,L)}{\partial K}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}F(K,L)}{\partial^{2}K}<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial F(K,L)}{\partial L}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}F(K,L)}{\partial^{2}L}<0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
First-order derivatives are just the marginal products of each input
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
e.g.
 adding the second cook should provide a significant increase in output,
 but the 10th cook provides much less
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
FF Curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Input Intensity of a Good
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Since there are now two factors used in production, goods must be different
 in terms of how dependent they are in each input
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Computers are more relatively capital intensive than textiles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Textiles are more relatively labour intensive than computers
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Input Intensity of a Good
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Definition: 
\emph on
A good is 
\series bold
relatively capital intensive
\series default
 if, for a given relative factor price, the capital-labour ratio used in
 production is higher than the capital-labour ratio used in the production
 of the other good
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relative factor price is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{w}{r}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the factor price of labour and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is the factor price of capital
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can represent differences in relative capital intensity using something
 called an 
\series bold
FF curve
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
FF Curve: Factor Prices and Input Ratio
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
For any fixed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{w}{r}$
\end_inset

, computers uses more capital relative to labour than textile
\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.065]{figures/l2b/ff1}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example with Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Suppose that computers are relatively capital intensive and textiles are
 relatively labour intensive
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Let's work through a numerical example
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
Q_{C}=K_{C}^{2/3}L_{C}^{1/3} &  & Q_{T}=K_{T}^{1/3}L_{T}^{2/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The powers in each input reflect the input intensity for the industry
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To get the optimal values of 
\begin_inset Formula $K_{C},\ K_{T},\ L_{C},\ L_{T}$
\end_inset

, need to maximize the profit functions
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{C}Q_{C}-rK_{C}-wL_{C}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{T}Q_{T}-rK_{T}-wL_{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take the derivatives of these profit functions with respect to each input
 to get the necessary conditions for optimal inputs
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example with Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{C}K_{C}^{2/3}L_{C}^{1/3}-rK_{C}-wL_{C}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{T}K_{T}^{1/3}L_{T}^{2/3}-rK_{T}-wL_{T}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These conditions show that at the optimal inputs, marginal cost = marginal
 revenue
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
w= & P_{T}\frac{2}{3}K_{T}^{1/3}L_{T}^{-1/3} & w=P_{C}\frac{1}{3}K_{C}^{2/3}L_{C}^{-2/3}\\
r= & P_{T}\frac{1}{3}K_{T}^{-2/3}L_{T}^{2/3} & r=P_{C}\frac{2}{3}K_{C}^{-1/3}L_{C}^{2/3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Take the ratio of wage to capital for each good
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\frac{w}{r}=2\frac{K_{T}}{L_{T}} &  & \frac{w}{r}=\frac{1}{2}\frac{K_{C}}{L_{C}}\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Example with Numbers
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


