\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Iso-Value Curves
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The iso-value curves maps the combinations of capital and labour that yield
 $1 of revenue
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Start with 
\begin_inset Formula $1=P_{C}F_{C}(K,L)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{C}(K,L)$
\end_inset

 is the production function of computers (it's also just output of computers
 for a given 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a given value of 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{C}$
\end_inset

, what values of 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 produce $1 of revenue?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These look a lot like the indifference curves in consumer theory
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Iso-Value Curves
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
Iso-value curves for prices 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{C,3}>P_{C,2}>P_{C,1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.065]{figures/l2b/ld2}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame

\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Iso-Cost Curves
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The iso-cost curves maps combinations of capital and labour that (as a bundle)
 cost $1
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Given 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, it is derived from cost function
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
wL+rK=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rearranging gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
K=\frac{1}{r}-\frac{w}{r}L
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We can draw this curve in our Lerner Diagram, noting that the slope of this
 equation is 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{w}{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Iso-Cost Curves
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


