centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.085]{figures/l2b/ld3}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Two conditions for an equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The equilibrium bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $(K^{*},L^{*})$
\end_inset

 must lie on both the iso-value and iso-cost curve
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
This is because perfect competition requires that revenue = cost
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If profits were positive, firms enter driving down prices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If profits were negative, firms exit driving up prices
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Both the iso-value and iso-cost curve have the same slope
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The slope of the iso-cost curve is just 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{w}{r}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
We still need to derive the iso-value slope
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
centering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
includegraphics[scale=.085]{figures/l2b/ld4a}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Slope of the Iso-Value Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The slope of iso-value curve is just the marginal rate of technical substitution
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It is an idea similar to the marginal rate of substitution from consumer
 theory
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To derive this, start with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=P_{C}F_{C}(K,L)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Move price to the left-hand side
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{P_{C}}=F_{C}(K,L)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Since the 1 here is the $1 revenue, 
\begin_inset Formula $1/P_{C}$
\end_inset

 is just the output (as you might expect since it's equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Slope of the Iso-Value Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In the Lerner Diagram we show the relationship between the input 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
as a function
\emph default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Keeping this in mind, take the total derivative of the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{P_{C}}=F_{C}(K,L)$
\end_inset

 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In other words, take the derivative of both sides of the equation with respect
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{d(1/P_{C})}{dL} & = & \frac{dF_{C}(K,L)}{dL}\\
 & = & \frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial K}\frac{dK}{dL}+\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial L}\frac{dL}{dL}\\
 & = & \frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial K}\frac{dK}{dL}+\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial L}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Slope of the Iso-Value Curve
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Multiply through by 
\begin_inset Formula $dL$
\end_inset

 and note the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $d(1/P_{C})=0$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $1/P_{C}$
\end_inset

 is a constant 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0=\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial K}dK+\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial L}dL
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Rearranging the expression above
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dK}{dL}=-\frac{\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial L}}{\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial K}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The ratios in the right side are the marginal products of labour and capital
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
They are a decreasing function of the inputs themselves based on our assumption
 on the production functions (e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial F(K,L)}{\partial K}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}F(K,L)}{\partial^{2}K}<0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial F(K,L)}{\partial L}>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\partial^{2}F(K,L)}{\partial^{2}L}<0$
\end_inset

)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Now that we have the slope of both the iso-cost and iso-value curves, we
 can solve for the equilibrium input bundle
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Iso-cost slope
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-\frac{w}{r}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Iso-value slope
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dK}{dL}=-\frac{\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial L}}{\frac{\partial F_{C}(K,L)}{\partial K}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Recall that the equilibrium conditions are
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
the equilibrium bundle 
\begin_inset Formula $(K^{*},L^{*})$
\end_inset

 must lie on both the iso-cost and iso-value curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
the slopes of the iso-cost and iso-value curves must be equal
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In consumer theory, the equilibrium bundle is such that the slope of the
 indifference curve is equal to the slope of the budget constraint
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Thus, the equilibrium set of inputs must be such that the iso-cost curve
 and the iso-value curves are 
\series bold
tangent
\series default
 to each other
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Separator

\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Lerner Diagram: Equilibrium
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

