\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
So far, we've been considering just one industry: computers
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With two industries, both industries share the same iso-cost curve
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
wage and rental rates are the same across industries due to perfect labour/capit
al mobility
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=rK+wL
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Their iso-value curves are different because each industry has its own productio
n function and face different prices
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
1 & = & P_{C}F_{C}(K,L)\\
1 & = & P_{T}F_{T}(K,L)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
